parsedComplaintsResult.impact: The failure of the torque converter can cause the transmission to overheat, leading to premature wear of transmission gears and eventual failure, which can leave the driver stranded or cause accidents.
symptoms: inability to move forward or reverse

parsedComplaintsResult.impact: The failure of the transmission cooling system can cause the transmission to overheat, leading to premature wear of transmission gears and eventual failure, which can leave the driver stranded or cause accidents.
symptoms: inability to move forward or reverse

parsedComplaintsResult.impact: The failure of defective transmission components, such as the aluminum planetary housing and gear, can cause transmission failure, leading to loss of control, accidents, and injuries.

The failure of the exhaust manifold studs can cause exhaust leaks, which can lead to the release of toxic fumes into the passenger compartment, posing a health risk to occupants. Additionally, it can cause the catalytic converter to overheat, potentially leading to a fire.
symptoms: exhaust fumes entering the passenger compartment
especially when the vehicle comes to a stop

parsedComplaintsResult.impact: The failure of the fuel/temperature gauge can cause the driver to be unaware of critical engine conditions, potentially leading to engine damage or overheating.
The failure of the EMC unit can cause the catalytic converter to overheat, potentially leading to a fire.
